where \(A\) is a \(2 \times 2\) matrix and \(T\) is a \(2 \times 2\) invertible matrix. The task is to find the matrix representation of \(\Phi\).

To find the matrix representation of \(\Phi\), we need to determine how \(\Phi\) acts on a general \(2 \times 2\) matrix \(A\). 

Let's consider an arbitrary \(2 \times 2\) matrix \(A\):

\[
A = \begin{pmatrix}
a & b \\
c & d
\end{pmatrix}
\]

The transformation \(\Phi(A)\) involves the matrix \(T\) and its inverse \(T^{-1}\). First, we apply \(T\) to \(A\):

\[
T A = \begin{pmatrix}
t_{11} & t_{12} \\
t_{21} & t_{22}
\end{pmatrix} \begin{pmatrix}
a & b \\
c & d
\end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix}
t_{11}a + t_{12}c & t_{11}b + t_{12}d \\
t_{21}a + t_{22}c & t_{21}b + t_{22}d
\end{pmatrix}
\]

Next, we apply \(T^{-1}\) to the result:

\[
\Phi(A) = T A T^{-1} = \begin{pmatrix}
t_{11}a + t_{12}c & t_{11}b + t_{12}d \\
t_{21}a + t_{22}c & t_{21}b + t_{22}d
\end{pmatrix} \begin{pmatrix}
t_{11}^{-1} & t_{12}^{-1} \\
t_{21}^{-1} & t_{22}^{-1}
\end{pmatrix}
\]

To find the final result, we compute the product of these two matrices:

\[
\Phi(A) = \begin{pmatrix}
(t_{11}a + t_{12}c)(t_{11}^{-1}) + (t_{11}b + t_{12}d)(t_{21}^{-1}) & (t_{11}a + t_{12}c)(t_{12}^{-1}) + (t_{11}b + t_{12}d)(t_{22}^{-1}) \\
